Vowel omissionAn Arabic syllable can be open (ending with a vowel) or closed (ending with a consonant):

open: CV [consonant-vowel] (long or short vowel)
closed: CVC (short vowel only)

In closed syllables, we can indicate that the closing consonant does not carry a vowel by marking it with a diacritic called {{transl}} ( {{script/Arabic}} &nbsp; ) to remove any ambiguity, especially when the text is not vocalized. A normal text is composed only of series of consonants; thus, the word {{transl}}, "heart", is written {{transl}}. The {{transl}} indicates where not to place a vowel: {{transl}} could, in effect, be read {{transl}} (meaning "he turned around"), but written with a {{transl}} over the {{transl}} and the {{transl}} ({{lang}}), it can only have the form {{transl}}. This is one step down from full vocalization, where the vowel {{transl}} would also be indicated by a {{transl}}: {{lang}}.The {{transl}} is traditionally written in full vocalization. Outside of the {{transl}}, putting a {{transl}} above a {{transl}} (representing {{IPA}}), or above a {{transl}} (representing {{IPA}}) is extremely rare, to the point that {{transl}} with {{transl}} will be unambiguously read as the diphthong {{IPA}}, and {{transl}} with {{transl}} will be read {{IPA}}. For example, the letters {{transl}} ({{lang}} with an {{transl}} at the end of the word)
will be read most naturally as the word {{transl}} ("music").  If one were to write a {{transl}} above the {{transl}}, the {{transl}} and the {{transl}}, one would get {{lang}}, which would be read as  {{transl}} (note however that the final {{transl}}, because it is an {{transl}}, never takes a {{transl}}).  The word, entirely vocalized, would be written as {{lang}}.  The Koranic spelling would have no {{transl}} sign above the final {{transl}}, but instead a miniature {{transl}} above the preceding {{transl}} consonant, which is a valid Unicode character but most Arabic computer fonts cannot in fact display this miniature {{transl}} as of 2006.No {{transl}} is placed on word-final consonants, even if no vowel is pronounced, because fully vocalized texts are always written as if  the {{transl}} vowels were in fact pronounced.  For example, {{transl}}, meaning “Ahmed is a wicked husband”, for the purposes of Arabic grammar and orthography, is treated as if still pronounced with full {{transl}}, i.e. {{transl}} with the complete desinences.

