The {{transl}} is also used for transliterating words into the Arabic script. The Persian word {{lang}} (mâsk, from the English word "mask"), for example, might be written with a {{transl}} above the {{lang}}  to signify that there is no vowel sound between that letter and the {{lang}}.
Additional letters

Regional variations

{{script/Arabic}} – a Maghrebi variation of the letter {{lang}} ({{transl}}) .



{{script/Arabic}} and {{script/Arabic}} – a Maghrebi variation of standard letter {{script/Arabic}} (as a rule, dotless in isolated and final positions and dotted in the initial and medial forms {{script/Arabic}}).

Additional modified letters, used in non-Arabic languages, or in Arabic for transliterating names, loanwords, spoken dialects only, include:
Sometimes used for writing names, loanwords and dialects

{{script/Arabic}} – (not to be confused with {{script/Arabic}}) used in Kurdish language when written in Arabic script and sometimes used in Arabic language to represent the sound {{IPAslink}} when transliterating names and loanwords in Arabic. Also used in writing dialects with that sound.Arabic Dialect Tutorial Usually the letter {{lang}} ({{transl}}) is used to transliterate {{IPAslink}}. Also used as pa in the Jawi script. The phoneme {{IPAslink}} in Tunisia and some other regions of Maghreb is rendered using {{script/Arabic}}.



{{lang}} – used to represent the phoneme {{IPAslink}} in Persian, Urdu, and Kurdish; sometimes used in Arabic language when transliterating names and loanwords, although Arabic mostly substitutes {{IPAslink}} for {{IPAslink}} in the transliteration of names and loanwords. So, &#34;7up&#34; can be transcribed as {{lang}} or {{script/Arabic}}.



{{lang}} – used to represent {{IPAslink}} (&#34;ch&#34;). It is used in Persian, Urdu, and Kurdish and sometimes used when transliterating names and loanwords in Arabic. In the Iraqi spoken dialect it may be used, especially when referring in the feminine, although it is rarely written, as well as rarely used in the Maghrebi spelling.  Nevertheless, Arabic usually substitutes other letters in the transliteration of names and loanwords: normally the combination {{lang}} ({{transl}}-{{transl}}) is used to transliterate the {{IPAslink}}, as in &#34;Chad&#34;. In Egypt {{lang}} is used for {{IPAslink}} (or {{IPAslink}}, which is approximated to {{IPAblink}}). In Israel, it&#39;s used to render {{IPAslink}} in Arabic language, for example on roadsigns.
Ca in the Jawi script.



{{lang}} – used to represent {{IPAslink}}. Normally used in Persian, Kurdish, and Urdu. Often names and loanwords with {{IPAslink}} are transliterated in Arabic with {{lang}} ({{transl}}), {{lang}} ({{transl}}), {{lang}} ({{transl}}) or {{lang}} ({{transl}}), which may or may not change the original sound. In Egypt {{lang}} is normally pronounced {{IPAblink}}.



{{lang}} – used to represent the voiced postalveolar fricative {{IPAslink}} in, Persian, Kurdish, Urdu and Uyghur.



{{script/Arabic}} – a Maghrebi letter, sometimes used for {{IPAblink}} (not to be confused with {{script/Arabic}}).  In Tunisia it is sometimes used to represent the phoneme {{IPAslink}}. In final and isolate form it has the form  which resembles the letter {{lang}} {{transl}} whence it is derived.



{{script/Arabic}} – a Maghrebi letter for {{IPAblink}}.


